const moonlightGardenPassage = `Read the passage and answer the questions.

**The Moonlight Garden**
*by Elena Brooks*

At the back of the town library stood a narrow courtyard surrounded by brick walls. Most visitors hurried past it without looking twice. During the day, the courtyard seemed plain: a few benches, a stone birdbath, and several empty planting beds outlined with old boards.

But at night, said Mrs. Alvarez, the librarian, the courtyard could become something special.

She shared her idea during the student helper meeting in early spring. "I want to create a moonlight garden," she said. "A place with flowers that shine pale in the evening and plants with silver leaves that catch the light."

Noah raised his hand. "Why would people visit a garden at night?"

Mrs. Alvarez smiled. "Because some things are easier to notice when the world gets quiet."

Most of the helpers liked the idea right away. Talia was not so sure. She preferred loud projects with bright posters and cheering crowds. A garden sounded slow.

Still, she signed up to help.

Every Wednesday after school, the helpers met in the courtyard. Mrs. Alvarez showed them how to loosen the soil and mix in compost. Mr. Chen from the plant nursery donated lamb's ear, white petunias, evening primrose, and tall grasses that whispered in the breeze. The students added smooth stones along the paths and painted old flowerpots deep blue.

At first, the garden did not look like much. The plants were small, and the courtyard still felt dusty and bare.

"It's like waiting for a story to start," Noah said.

Talia shrugged. "I hope it gets to the interesting part soon."

Weeks passed. The students watered, weeded, and tied labels to wooden sticks. They also hung tiny metal bells beside the gate and strung soft white lights along the wall. One afternoon, Talia noticed that the lamb's ear leaves looked almost silver. Another day, she bent to smell the primrose and caught a sweet scent that seemed strongest near sunset.

By June, the courtyard had changed. White blossoms glowed against the dark soil. Pale stones curved through the beds like a small river. The grasses lifted and bowed when the evening wind moved through them. When the lights switched on, the whole place seemed to float.

Mrs. Alvarez invited families to the library for the opening night. She asked the student helpers to guide visitors through the garden and read short poems aloud.

That evening, Talia arrived just as the sun was dropping behind the roof of the library. She stopped at the gate and stared.

The courtyard looked larger than she remembered. Fireflies blinked above the grass. The white flowers shone in the deep blue air. Parents whispered as if they had stepped into a chapel. A toddler reached for the bells and laughed when they chimed softly.

Noah came up beside Talia. "Interesting enough yet?" he asked.

Talia did not answer right away. She was watching the moon rise above the wall.

"Yeah," she said finally. "I think quiet things can be interesting too."

Later, after the visitors left, the student helpers sat on the benches eating slices of pear tart from the bakery next door. No one hurried to leave. The courtyard held the cool air, the flower scent, and the moonlight all at once.

Mrs. Alvarez looked around at the garden and then at the students. "You gave this place a second life," she said.

Talia touched one of the silvery leaves beside her bench. For once, she did not feel like saying anything. The garden already seemed to be speaking for itself.`;

const wetlandsPassage = `Read the passage and answer the questions.

**Why Wetlands Matter**
*adapted from environmental education sources*

Wetlands are places where land is covered by shallow water for part or all of the year. Some wetlands are marshes full of grasses, while others are swamps with trees and shrubs. At first glance, a wetland may look muddy, still, or even empty. In fact, wetlands are some of the busiest and most important ecosystems on Earth.

**Homes for Wildlife**

Many animals depend on wetlands. Frogs lay eggs in calm water. Ducks and herons nest among reeds. Fish use wetland areas as safe places to rest or grow before moving into deeper rivers, lakes, or oceans. Insects, turtles, and mammals also rely on wetlands for food and shelter.

**Natural Sponges**

Wetlands act like giant sponges during storms. When heavy rain falls, wetlands can hold extra water and slow flooding. This helps protect nearby neighborhoods, farms, and roads. Later, some of that water slowly moves back into streams and underground supplies.

**Cleaning the Water**

Wetlands can also help clean water. As water moves through wetland plants and soil, mud and pollution can get trapped. This does not remove every harmful material, but it can improve water quality. Scientists often compare wetlands to natural filters.

**Changing Over Time**

Wetlands are always changing. A wetland may grow larger after rainy years and shrink during dry seasons. New plants move in. Animal populations rise and fall. Because wetlands are connected to weather, water, and living things, they are always in motion even when they appear quiet.

**Why Wetlands Need Protection**

For many years, people drained wetlands to build roads, stores, and neighborhoods. Some wetlands were filled with dirt because people did not understand how useful they were. Today, many communities protect wetlands by limiting pollution, restoring native plants, and creating boardwalks so visitors can learn without damaging the habitat.

Protecting wetlands helps both wildlife and people. A healthy wetland can reduce flooding, improve water quality, and support many kinds of life all at once.`;

const bellTowerPassage = `Read the passage and answer the questions.

**The Map in the Bell Tower**
*by James Holloway*

The old meeting hall stood at the top of Maple Street, where the road bent toward the harbor. Its clock had stopped years ago, and no one in town could remember the last time the bell rang. On rainy days, the building smelled like wood dust and salt.

Leah had visited the hall many times with her grandfather, who repaired broken furniture in the workshop downstairs. While he sanded chair legs and glued drawers, Leah explored the corners of the building. She liked the narrow staircases, the dusty framed photographs, and the high windows that looked out toward the water.

One Saturday, Grandfather handed her a feather duster. "If you're going to explore," he said, "you can at least make yourself useful."

Leah laughed and climbed the stairs to the bell tower.

At the top, sunlight came through the slats and striped the floorboards. Pigeons fluttered from a beam when she opened the hatch. Leah sneezed, wiped dust from a wooden chest, and noticed that one of its brass hinges looked newer than the others.

That was odd.

The chest was empty except for a cracked lantern, a length of rope, and a loose board resting flat against the bottom. When Leah lifted the board, she found a folded sheet of thick paper tucked beneath it.

She carried it downstairs.

"Grandfather," she said, "look at this."

He set down his glue brush and unfolded the paper with careful hands. It was a map of the harbor from long ago. Small notes crowded the edges in faded ink. One sentence, written darker than the rest, caught Leah's eye:

**For the safest return, follow the bell in fog.**

"What does that mean?" Leah asked.

Grandfather leaned closer. "This hall used to ring the harbor bell during storms," he said. "Before the modern lighthouse was built, ships listened for it when they could not see the shore."

Leah imagined boats moving through gray water while sailors strained to hear the bell. "So the map was helping them?"

"Maybe," Grandfather said. "Or maybe it reminded the bell ringer where danger was."

The two of them studied the markings. Some showed shallow sandbars. Others pointed to jagged rocks near the point. Along one edge, a narrow pencil line curved through the channel like a trail.

"Could we show this to the history museum?" Leah asked.

Grandfather nodded. "We should. But first, let's make sure we understand what we found."

Over the next week, Leah returned after school. She copied symbols from the map into a notebook and compared them with modern harbor charts in the library. She learned that some rocks had been blasted away many years earlier and that the shoreline had shifted after a major storm. But the main channel was still there.

On Thursday, she noticed that the pencil line on the old map matched almost exactly with the safest route marked on the modern chart.

"It wasn't just decoration," Leah said that evening. "The line was real."

Grandfather smiled. "Someone drew it because it mattered."

The museum director invited Leah and her grandfather to bring the map to a community history night. People crowded around the display table as Leah explained what the notes meant. Several fishermen pointed at the sandbar markings and said their grandparents used the same names.

Near the end of the evening, the museum director cleared her throat. "We have been trying to convince the town council to restore the bell tower," she said. "I think this map gives us a new reason."

A week later, workers oiled the bell wheel and replaced a cracked beam. The town did not plan to use the bell during storms anymore, but they wanted visitors to hear what sailors once depended on.

At the reopening ceremony, Leah stood beside her grandfather in the crowd. When the mayor pulled the rope, the bell gave a deep bronze note that rolled over the harbor and out across the water.

Leah felt the sound in her chest before it faded into the wind. For a moment, the whole town seemed to be listening backward in time.`;

const volcanoPassage = `Read the passage and answer the questions.

**How Volcanoes Build New Land**
*adapted from earth science sources*

When people hear the word volcano, they often think first of explosions, smoke, and danger. Volcanoes can certainly be destructive. But volcanoes can also create. Over long periods of time, volcanic activity can build mountains, islands, and fresh rock that becomes new land.

**Magma and Lava**

Deep inside Earth, melted rock is called magma. When magma rises through cracks and reaches the surface, it is called lava. As lava cools, it hardens into rock. One eruption may add only a small amount of new material, but many eruptions over hundreds or thousands of years can change the shape of an entire region.

**Building Islands**

Some volcanic islands rise from the ocean floor. Layer by layer, cooled lava builds upward until the volcano reaches the water's surface. If eruptions continue, the island grows larger. The Hawaiian Islands formed this way over a very long time.

**Changing the Landscape**

Volcanoes do not always build land in the same way. Some produce broad, gently sloping mountains because their lava spreads easily. Others form steep cones from thicker lava, ash, and rock. After eruptions, wind and rain begin wearing the new rock down. Plants may take root in cracks. Eventually, animals and people may live on land that did not exist before.

**From Rock to Soil**

Fresh volcanic rock is hard and rough. At first, very little can grow on it. Over time, weathering breaks the rock into smaller pieces. Dead plants and tiny living things add more material. Slowly, soil forms. This process can take many years, but it allows grasses, shrubs, and trees to grow.

**Living Near Volcanoes**

Millions of people live near volcanoes around the world. Volcanic areas can be risky, but they also offer benefits. Ash and broken volcanic rock can create rich soil for farming. Some volcanic regions provide hot springs or geothermal energy. Scientists study volcanoes carefully so they can warn communities when activity changes.

Volcanoes remind us that Earth is always being reshaped. The same forces that can destroy homes in one moment can, over time, build entirely new landscapes.`;

